@Nift -- This is a great idea and I appreciate you getting the ball rolling on this. I'm a python3 n00b, but I look forward to figuring this out.

@nesnahnoj -- thanks for bringing this to the top of my inbox today and for putting a vote to having python3 support. As you'll see below, I had a few lingering things that I haven't had the time to jot down. Please accept my apologies for my relatively slow response.

I'm admittedly having a very hard time following this pull request though, and I do not think I can figure out how to merge this in on my own. This pull request includes a lot of files copied into the `textract` directory (all of them?), causing nearly the entire codebase to be duplicated inside of that directory. The `textract` directory is intended to only hold the python code of the package, not all of the other cruft that's necessary for development, documentation, testing, etc. This makes it very difficult to understand what, specifically, had to change to provide python3 support. **I'm going to close this particular pull request, but its my sincere hope that we incorporate python3 support.**

@Nift -- If you or anyone else would like to create a separate pull request that provides python3 support, I'd encourage you to [create a feature branch](https://guides.github.com/introduction/flow/) based off of the current `deanmalmgren/master` branch and only change the files that are necessary to incorporate python3 support. I would be happy to hop on skype/hangout/etc to help you get started if you'd like. 

Admittedly, I don't know a whole lot about python3, but here are a few things that I think are important to keep in mind as we adapt textract to being python3 compatible:

1. I would like to understand how bigger python projects manage both the python2 and python3 support. I could imagine handling this either (i) by adapting having the codebase support python2 and python3 simultaneously and making releases on the same 1.x version sequence, (ii) by killing python2 after the next 1.x version release and only continue support in python3 starting in the 2.x version release, or (iii) by maintaining support for python2 and python3 on separate branches and releasing python3 releases on a new 2.x version sequence. I'm leaning toward options (ii) or maybe (iii), simply because it makes the code less kludgy and easier to maintain, but I'd appreciate input from anyone else that has experience with this or preferences one way or another. Advice welcome!

2. My understanding is that python3 has a much more straightforward treatment of byte string encodings and unicode. I'm not sure how that will impact many of the parsers, but several of the command line tools output byte-encoded strings. This is why we create a [unicode sandwich](https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/blob/master/textract/parsers/utils.py#L33-L46) when we process output from command line tools (and other tools) and why we have [to guess the encoding](https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/blob/master/textract/parsers/utils.py#L61-L64) of the incoming byte string. Python 3 may make this easier, but we should address this situation in a consistent way.

3. I have no idea how many of [textract's dependencies](https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/blob/master/requirements/python) are python3 compatible. Ideally we wouldn't have to sacrifice any currently supported functionality when we make the python3 switch, but I'm not necessarily married to that. @Nift mentioned pdfminer is an issue; are there others? 

I can't think of anything else, but this list of concerns is one of the reason it took me a while to respond to this pull request. Thanks again to @Nift for getting the ball rolling on this, and I look forward to working with you and others to get python3 incorporated in a separate PR soon.

