Turns out, I needed this. And since I use Redis for my Django cache backend, I could use `cache.lock()`. See this blog post: https://www.peterbe.com/plog/django-lock-decorator-with-django-redis

Basically, we could add an option to `django-cache-memoize` that does this stuff but we'll put in the docs "You have to use django-redis for this to work". 

Or, for people who *don't* use `django-redis` but have a Redis connection available, they could pass in an instance of it. E.g.

```python
@cache_memoize(100, lock=True)
def expensive_function(start, end):
    return random.randint(start, end)
```

Or

```python
import redis.client
_redis = redis.client.Redis(config)


@cache_memoize(100, lock=True, redis=_redis)
def expensive_function(start, end):
    return random.randint(start, end)
```

What do you think?

@tushar00jain when you say, *"I want the computations within the same batch to happen in parallel"*... I'm not quite sure what you mean...

Multiple workers allow for "data-parallelism".  Multiple PS nodes allow for "model-parallelism".  In your case, I assume that you're looking for "data-parallelism"... but that implies that each worker (at least per your current code), will process a **different** batch of input data, train, compute their own gradients, and then update the PS (where the PS is responsible for updating/aggregating the parameters from the workers).

That all said, if you want to literally compute one batch of data across multiple workers, then you will have to start playing with device placement of your ops.  Just beware that there will be network costs, e.g. if one worker reads the batch, but has to distribute the data to other workers...

