I'm running Nginx 1.10.3 on an Ubuntu 16.04.3 LTS server and ran into a problem using the HTTP-01 challenge with one of my domains because the `.well-known` directory was not publicly accessible. The least-disruptive way I found to resolve this was to add a directive in the `server` section of my `.conf` file for the domain. The following example tells Nginx where to find the `.well-known` directory and allows anyone to view it:

```
server {
  server_name example.com
  ...
  location ~ /.well-known {
    root /path/to/nginx/webroot
    allow all;
  }
  location / {
    ...
  }
}
```

I tested the configuration with `sudo nginx -t` and after the test passed I enabled it with `sudo service nginx reload`

Note: The root directory in that location section must be the same one that you use in your certbot command:

`sudo certbot --authenticator webroot --webroot-path /path/to/nginx/webroot --installer nginx -d example.com`

I hope this helps at least one other person.

